## Consolidated System Engineering Blueprint (English Documentation)## 1. Fundamental Physical Correction
It is physically impossible to change the molecular chirality of cholesterol in the entire human body by touching a capacitive screen. Molecular chirality is a fixed structural parameter defined by its 8 asymmetric carbon centers.
Instead, by adding a graphene layer to the screen, we pivot the experiment into a quantum-mechanical touch sensor. The system generates Negative Differential Resistance (NDR) and Fractional Negative Differential Resistance (FNDR) locally through mechanical strain and resonant electron tunneling.
## 2. Physical Sensor Architecture
To capture localized NDR, the screen is engineered as a macro-matrix of microscopic Molecular Tunneling Junctions (MTJ) distributed across touch pixels:

    [ Human Finger / Applied Mechanical Force ]
======================================================
  1. Protective Overlayer (Ultra-thin Hexagonal Boron Nitride or Polymer)
  2. Twisted Bilayer Graphene - tBLG (Top Flexible Work Electrode)
  3. Quantum Tunneling Barrier (Self-assembled Lipid/Cholesterol Monolayer, ~2-3 nm)
  4. Indium Tin Oxide - ITO Grid (Bottom Fixed Counter Electrode)
======================================================
    [ Glass Substrate / Display TFT Array Matrix ]


* Graphene Selection: Twisted Bilayer Graphene (tBLG) set near the "magic angle" ($1.1^\circ$) is ideal. Mechanical compression modifies the interlayer distance and local moiré lattice parameters. This shifts the flat-band electronic density of states, triggering an abrupt phase transition and strong NDR signatures at low activation voltages.

## 3. Hardware Measuring Circuit & Stability Criteria

  +------------------ Source Measure Unit (SMU) -------------------+

  |                                                                |
  |   [ AC+DC Ramp Generator ] ---> ( Rs ) ---> [ Graphene Pixel ] |
  |                                      |            (Device)     |
  |                                      v              |          |
  |                             [ Transimpedance ]     v          |
  |                             [ Amplifier - TIA ] --->(GND)      |
  |                                      |                         |
  +--------------------------------------|-------------------------+
                                         v
                            [ High-Speed ADC Converter ]

To read the NDR region stably without entering uncontrolled high-frequency self-oscillations, the system instrumentation must meet the strict DC stability criterion:
$$R_s > \left\vert{} -R_{NDR} \right\vert{}$$ 
Where $R_s$ is a precise series load resistor, and $\left\vert{} -R_{NDR} \right\vert{}$ is the absolute peak value of the device's negative differential resistance.
## 4. Software Analysis Pipeline (FNDR Processing)

   1. DC Sweep Analysis: The application filters the micro-ampere level raw data with a Savitzky-Golay filter to strip out display EMI matrix noise. It computes the first numerical derivative ($\frac{dI}{dV}$). A verified NDR zone is declared whenever the differential conductance drops below zero ($\frac{dI}{dV} < 0$).
   2. AC Fractional (FNDR) Analysis: To isolate the Fractional component caused by the quantum capacitance delays of graphene, an AC perturbation signal ($\tilde{v} = V_{0}\sin(\omega t)$) is superimposed over the DC ramp. The software runs a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) or digital lock-in algorithm on the output current stream to resolve the complex admittance vector:
   $$Y(\omega) = G(\omega) + j\omega C_q$$ 
   FNDR is mathematically extracted by fitting the frequency dispersion curves to anomalous fractional-order models (non-integer power-law exponents), mapping capacitive phase delays across the sensor layout.

